bic-speaking world. It has probably enjoyed a longer shelf-life than any other logic textbook ever written, having been in use by madrasah students from the early eighth/fourteenth century up until the present day. Building on the theories of Avicenna, al-Rāzī, and other pioneers of logic, al-Kātibī discusses the many pitfalls of building arguments and setting out unambiguous claims in natural language. The enduring nature of the text is a testament to al-Kātibī and his impact on concepts of formal discourse and argument. This new translation of The Rules of Logic brings to both an Arabic and English readership an influential text that has shaped the work of scholars of logic for centuries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aLogicvEarly works to 18002DLC. 0aLogicvEarly works to 1800. 7aPOETRY / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh  aarabic literature.  aarabic logic.  aarabic philosophy.  aarabic to english translation.  aarabic translation.  abilingual.  aeleventh century.  aislam.  aislamic literature.  alibrary of arabic literature.  alogic.  amedieval arabic literature.  ametaphysics.  amuslim literature.  amuslim.  aphilosopher.  aphilosophy book.  aphilosophy.  averse.1 aStreet, Tony, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075164240uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479864706.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479864706423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479864706/original  a978-3-11-075164-2  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles